05288nam a22006495i 9780226456829DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20162015ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264568297 a10.7208/97802264568292doi  a(DE-B1597)523609  a(OCoLC)1086524938  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aKF5599b.S66 2017 7aLAW0000002bisacsh04a343.7302522231 aSomin, Ilya, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Grasping Hand :b"Kelo v. City of New London" and the Limits of Eminent Domain /cIlya Somin. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2016] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b6 halftones, 1 line drawing, 1  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface to the Paperback Edition -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. The Trouble in Fort Trumbull -- tChapter 2. From Public Use to Public Purpose -- tChapter 3. The Perils of Public Purpose -- tChapter 4. The Kelo Decision -- tChapter 5. The Political Backlash -- tChapter 6. Why the Backlash Often Fell Short -- tChapter 7. The Judicial Reaction -- tChapter 8. Should Blight and Economic Development Takings Be Reformed or Banned? -- tConclusion -- tAppendix A -- tAppendix B -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 2005, the Supreme Court ruled that the city of New London, Connecticut, could condemn fifteen residential properties in order to transfer them to a new private owner. Although the Fifth Amendment only permits the taking of private property for "public use," the Court ruled that the transfer of condemned land to private parties for "economic development" is permitted by the Constitution-even if the government cannot prove that the expected development will ever actually happen. The Court's decision in Kelo v. City of New London empowered the grasping hand of the state at the expense of the invisible hand of the market. In this detailed study of one of the most controversial Supreme Court cases in modern times, Ilya Somin argues that Kelo was a grave error. Economic development and "blight" condemnations are unconstitutional under both originalist and most "living constitution" theories of legal interpretation. They also victimize the poor and the politically weak for the benefit of powerful interest groups and often destroy more economic value than they create. Kelo itself exemplifies these patterns. The residents targeted for condemnation lacked the influence needed to combat the formidable government and corporate interests arrayed against them. Moreover, the city's poorly conceived development plan ultimately failed: the condemned land lies empty to this day, occupied only by feral cats. The Supreme Court's unpopular ruling triggered an unprecedented political reaction, with forty-five states passing new laws intended to limit the use of eminent domain. But many of the new laws impose few or no genuine constraints on takings. The Kelo backlash led to significant progress, but not nearly as much as it may have seemed. Despite its outcome, the closely divided 5-4 ruling shattered what many believed to be a consensus that virtually any condemnation qualifies as a public use under the Fifth Amendment. It also showed that there is widespread public opposition to eminent domain abuse. With controversy over takings sure to continue, The Grasping Hand offers the first book-length analysis of Kelo by a legal scholar, alongside a broader history of the dispute over public use and eminent domain and an evaluation of options for reform.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aEminent domainzUnited StatesxCases. 0aZoning lawzUnited StatesxCases. 4aKelo. 4aSupreme Court. 4a